# Voltage Divider

Two resistors in series across a source split the input voltage in
proportion to their resistances. This is the single most reused idea in
analog electronics — bias networks, sensor interfaces, level shifters,
volume controls, and the first stage of most op-amp configurations all
start here.

$$
V_\text{out} = V_\text{in}\,\frac{R_2}{R_1 + R_2}
$$

We walk a concrete 12 V source through three pairs of resistors and watch
the output tap move.

```text
1. KVL around the loop: V_in = I (R1 + R2)
2. Current I = V_in / (R1 + R2)
3. V_out = I * R2 = V_in * R2 / (R1 + R2)
4. Change the ratio, V_out scales with it.
```

