## Quiz

?? What happens to $V_\text{out}$ if a load resistor $R_L$ is connected from the output tap to ground, and $R_L$ is comparable to $R_2$?
>> $R_L$ appears in parallel with $R_2$, lowering the lower-leg resistance to $R_2 \| R_L$. That shifts the divider ratio and $V_\text{out}$ drops. A rule of thumb: make $R_L \gtrsim 10\,R_2$ to keep loading error under ~10 %, or buffer the output with an op-amp voltage follower.

?? You need $V_\text{out} = 3.3\text{ V}$ from a 5 V rail. Give a sensible pair of resistor values and explain the tradeoff between small and large values.
>> Any pair with ratio $R_2/(R_1+R_2) = 0.66$ works — e.g. $R_1 = 1.7\text{ k}\Omega, R_2 = 3.3\text{ k}\Omega$, or $10\times$ that. Smaller resistors waste more power ($P = V_\text{in}^2/(R_1+R_2)$) but load better; larger resistors save power but are noisier and more sensitive to the downstream load. In the kΩ–tens of kΩ range for signal dividers is usually right.
